message.content: Pinus radiata, commonly known as Monterey pine, is a species of evergreen coniferous tree native to the Central Coast of California. It can grow up to 60 meters tall and has a straight trunk with horizontal branches. The needles are a blue-green color and are approximately 15 cm long. The bark is thick and rough with a reddish-brown color. The cones are 8-17 cm long and have a conical shape with sharp, thin scales. Pinus radiata is a valuable timber tree and is widely planted for forestation, especially in New Zealand. It is also used for erosion control and landscaping purposes.
